  "prompt": "What is indirect recursion?",
  "response": "Indirect recursion occurs when a function calls another function, which in turn calls the first function, creating a cycle of calls between them. This is different from direct recursion, where a function calls itself directly.\n\nFor example, consider two functions, `A` and `B`:\n\n```python\ndef A():\n    print(\"Function A is called\")\n    B()\n\ndef B():\n    print(\"Function B is called\")\n    A()\n```\n\nIn this scenario, calling function `A()` will lead to `B()` being called, which will then call `A()` again, and so on, creating a cycle of calls. This continues until a termination condition is met (if one is defined) or until a stack overflow occurs due to excessive function calls.\n\nIndirect recursion can be useful in certain scenarios where the behavior of the functions is intertwined, allowing for more complex structures and interactions between different parts of a program. However, it's important to manage the recursion depth carefully to avoid performance issues or crashes due to infinite recursion.",
